"""
MKT Original Commentary — Matthew chapters 1–4
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-matthew-1-4.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/matthew.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/matthew.json
- data/translation/notes/matthew.json
- data/commentary/mkt-original/matthew.json (existing entries)

Key decisions in this range:
- biblos geneseos (1:1): LXX Gen 5:1 echo — deliberate new-genesis framing
- Women in genealogy (1:3,5,6): ek + genitive singles out maternal contribution
- mnesteutheises (1:18): betrothal = legally binding, divorce required to dissolve
- ek pneumatos hagiou (1:18,20): ek = source/origin of conception
- gegraptai (4:4,7,10): perfect = stands written, not merely historical fact
- anechthe (4:1) passive: Spirit as the agent of wilderness-leading
- eutheos (4:20,22): Matthean immediacy marker for discipleship response
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p><strong>biblos geneseos</strong> (<em>biblos geneseos</em>) — book of the origin/genealogy — the same phrase as LXX Gen 5:1 (<em>haute he biblos geneseos anthropon</em>). Matthew deliberately opens with the creation-formula, presenting Jesus as inaugurating a new genesis. <strong>Iesou Christou</strong> — Jesus Christ — the name first, immediately followed by both titles: <em>huiou Dauid</em> (son of David, the royal Messianic line) and <em>huiou Abraam</em> (son of Abraham, the covenant promise-bearer). The reverse order (David before Abraham) emphasizes the Messianic dimension first; then the founding covenant is named.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The genealogical formula <strong>egennesen</strong> (aorist of <em>gennao</em>, to father, beget) runs throughout vv.2-16, establishing the chain of legal covenant descent. The first entry names Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, then specifies <em>Iouda kai tous adelphous autou</em> — Judah and his brothers — the first appearance of "brothers" signals the wider family unit even as the Messianic line passes through the specific son. The Greek <em>egennesen</em> is the technical genealogical verb, equivalent to the Hebrew <em>holid</em> in the OT toledot formulas.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The first of four women in the genealogy: <strong>ex autes</strong> — from/out of her — the preposition <em>ek</em> with the genitive feminine pronoun (<em>autes</em>) singles out the maternal contribution, departing from the uniform <em>egennesen</em> formula to flag the irregular or notable circumstance. Tamar (Gen 38) bore Perez and Zerah to her father-in-law Judah through a deception she resorted to when he withheld her rightful marriage. Matthew includes her without explanation, leaving the reader to supply the narrative context.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The genealogical formula continues without interruption from v.2 through v.16. These verses establish the covenant lineage through which the Messianic promise (2 Sam 7:12-16; Ps 89) passes. The names in vv.4-6 (Ram, Amminadab, Nahshon, Salmon) bridge the wilderness generation to the period of the judges and the establishment of the monarchy — each link in the chain is necessary to the Davidic credential that the genealogy establishes for Jesus.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Two more women appear: <strong>Rahab</strong> (a Gentile prostitute of Jericho, Josh 2; 6:25) and <strong>Ruth</strong> (a Moabite widow, Ruth 1-4). Both are Gentiles incorporated into the Israelite community through covenant faithfulness. Rahab: <em>ek tes Raab</em>; Ruth: <em>ek tes Routh</em>. The same <em>ek</em> construction marks each woman. Matthew\'s inclusion of Gentile women in the Messianic genealogy anticipates the Gospel\'s movement toward all nations (28:19).</p>',
    "6": '<p>The fourth notable woman: <strong>ek tes tou Ouriou</strong> — from the wife of Uriah — Bathsheba is not named; she is identified by her dead husband\'s name, emphasizing the adultery that was the context of Solomon\'s conception (2 Sam 11-12). The periphrasis keeps the moral reality visible: Jesus\'s lineage passes through covenant violation as well as covenant faithfulness. The inclusion of all four women signals that the genealogy does not idealize the Messianic line\'s history.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The post-Solomonic period: Rehoboam (<em>Roboam</em>), Abijah (<em>Abia</em>), Asa. These names carry the weight of the divided kingdom period and Israel\'s repeated covenant failures. Matthew does not editorialize; the genealogy moves forward through the historical chain, including kings who were largely unfaithful, because the covenant promise to David (2 Sam 7:16) was unconditional in its ultimate scope. The lineage passes through the kings despite their failures.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Verse 8 omits three kings between Joram and Uzziah: Ahaziah, Joash, and Amaziah (cf. 1 Chr 3:11-12). Matthew\'s selective genealogy follows the practice of OT genealogies that sometimes omit names for literary or theological purposes. The omissions may reflect a deliberate 14-14-14 structuring (v.17) or judgments about dynasties contaminated by Ahab\'s house (through Ahaziah\'s mother Athaliah). The LXX and MT genealogies themselves vary, and Matthew\'s authority is his apostolic presentation, not genealogical completeness.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The genealogical chain continues through the late Judahite monarchy: Uzziah (= Azariah in Kings), Jotham, Ahaz, Hezekiah — a period marked by the growing Assyrian threat that culminated in the northern kingdom\'s fall (722 BCE). The names carry narrative freight for readers familiar with the history, but Matthew\'s genealogy abstracts them into the covenantal chain: each king is a necessary link in the Davidic promise moving toward its culmination in Jesus.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Hezekiah, Manasseh, Amos/Amon, Josiah — the final pre-exilic generation. Manasseh was the most apostate of Judah\'s kings (2 Kgs 21:1-18); Josiah was the great reformer (2 Kgs 22-23). The contrast within a single genealogical sequence demonstrates that the Messianic line did not depend on consistent covenant faithfulness in its bearers. The promise endures through the worst of Israel\'s kings as well as the best.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>epi tes metoikesias Babylonos</strong> — at the time of the Babylonian exile (<em>metoikesia</em> = deportation, change of residence by force) — Matthew uses <em>metoikesia</em> (also v.12, 17) rather than the harsher <em>aichmalōsia</em> (captivity, imprisonment) perhaps to emphasize the displacement dimension rather than the penal one. The exile is the structural pivot of the genealogy\'s three sections (v.17). Jechoniah (= Jehoiachin) is the king taken to Babylon (2 Kgs 24:15).</p>',
    "12": '<p>The post-exilic section of the genealogy (<em>meta de ten metoikesian Babylonos</em> = after the Babylonian exile) continues from Jechoniah through Shealtiel and Zerubbabel — the restoration figures (Ezra, Nehemiah, Haggai, Zechariah). Zerubbabel was the governor of the returned community and a Davidic figure around whom royal hopes clustered (Hag 2:23; Zech 4:6-10). The genealogy passes through the restoration generation on its way to the birth of Jesus.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The post-Zerubbabel section enters the period of Second Temple Judaism where no biblical genealogies exist: Abiud, Eliakim, Azor are otherwise unknown from canonical sources. Matthew either had access to Davidic family genealogical records or worked from traditional sources. The names are historically plausible (all are common Second Temple Jewish names) but cannot be independently verified. The genealogy is making a legal and theological claim about Jesus\'s Davidic descent, not a purely archival historical record.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The genealogy continues through the otherwise unattested post-exilic figures: Zadok, Achim, Eliud. The covenant chain is maintained through the dark centuries of Persian, Ptolemaic, and Seleucid rule when the Davidic dynasty held no political power. The genealogy preserves the claim that the legal heir to the Davidic throne continued to exist even when no Davidic king ruled — a historically significant claim for a 1st-century Jewish audience familiar with the messianic expectation.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The final generation before Joseph: Eleazar, Matthan, Jacob. The name Jacob echoes the patriarch, creating an inclusio with Abraham (v.2): the genealogy begins with the founding patriarch and ends with the patriarch\'s name repeated one generation before the climax. <em>Iakōb de egennesen ton Iōseph</em> — Jacob fathered Joseph — the repetition of the patriarch name immediately before Joseph (the patriarch Joseph\'s namesake) strengthens the typological resonance: as the patriarch Joseph brought salvation to Israel through suffering, so this Joseph becomes the legal father of the one who saves.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>Iōseph ton andra Marias</strong> — Joseph the husband of Mary — a grammatical pivot: all previous <em>egennesen</em> entries say "A was the father of B"; here the formula shifts to <em>ex hes egennethe Iesous</em> — from whom Jesus was born. The masculine genealogical formula is broken precisely at the point of the virgin birth: Joseph is identified as Mary\'s husband, not as Jesus\'s biological father. <em>Ho legomenos Christos</em> — the one called Christ — the appended title marks Jesus as the culmination of the entire 42-generation sequence.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>Pasai oun hai geneai apo Abraam heos Dauid geneai dekatessares</strong> — thus all the generations from Abraham to David are fourteen generations — the triple fourteen pattern (14-14-14: Abraham→David, David→exile, exile→Christ) may reflect <em>gematria</em>: the numerical value of David\'s name in Hebrew (<em>dalet</em>=4, <em>vav</em>=6, <em>dalet</em>=4 = 14), making the genealogy itself a literary-numerical declaration that Jesus is the Son of David. Matthew\'s arrangement required selective omission of some kings (v.8), a recognized genealogical convention.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>mnesteutheises</strong> (<em>mnesteuo</em>) — betrothed, engaged — Jewish betrothal (<em>erusin</em>) was legally binding, not merely a modern engagement; breaking it required a divorce (v.19 <em>apolyein</em> = to release/divorce). <strong>ek pneumatos hagiou</strong> — of/from the Holy Spirit — the preposition <em>ek</em> denotes origin: the conception is sourced from the Holy Spirit, not from human generation. <strong>prin e synelthein autous</strong> — before they came together — the verb <em>synerchomai</em> here denotes cohabitation; the clarification establishes that the pregnancy preceded the beginning of married life.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>Iōseph de ho aner autes dikaios on</strong> — Joseph her husband, being a righteous man — <em>dikaios</em> (righteous) describes one who observes Torah faithfully. His plan to divorce Mary <strong>lathrai</strong> (secretly, quietly) means using the private bill of divorce rather than public accusation (Deut 22:23-24 would have required stoning if adultery were publicly alleged). <strong>Apolyein auten</strong> — to release/divorce her — the legal vocabulary confirms the betrothal\'s binding status: <em>apolyein</em> is the same verb for divorce of a married woman (5:31-32). Joseph\'s mercy goes beyond Torah\'s minimum requirement.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>kat\' onar</strong> — in a dream — Matthew uses this phrase five times (1:20; 2:12, 13, 19, 22) for divine communication, corresponding to OT dream-revelation (Gen 37-40; Dan 2, 7). <strong>Iōseph huios Dauid</strong> — Joseph son of David — the angel\'s address identifies Joseph\'s Davidic genealogy as the legal basis for Jesus\'s Davidic sonship: the legal father (even if not biological) transmits the lineage. <strong>Mē phobēthēs paralabein Marian ten gynaika sou</strong> — do not fear to take Mary as your wife — the aorist infinitive <em>paralabein</em> (to take alongside, to receive) confirms that the consummation of the marriage had not yet occurred.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>touto de holon gegonen hina plerothe</strong> — all this happened in order that it might be fulfilled — the <em>hina</em> (in order that) with subjunctive indicates divine purpose: the events were arranged for fulfillment, not merely correlated. <strong>plerothe</strong> (aorist passive subjunctive of <em>pleroo</em>) — filled up, completed. Matthew\'s fulfillment formula (<em>to rhēthen hypo kyriou dia tou prophētou</em> = what was spoken by the Lord through the prophet) traces the divine word through two agents: the Lord (<em>kyrios</em>) as the primary speaker, the prophet as the instrument. This form of the formula appears 11 times in Matthew.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>egertheis de ho Iōseph apo tou hypnou epoiesen hos prosetaxen auto ho angelos kyriou</strong> — Joseph, having been aroused from sleep, did as the angel of the Lord commanded him. The participle <em>egertheis</em> (having been aroused/raised up) is the same root as the resurrection verb (<em>egeiro</em>), though here merely "woke." The obedience formula (<em>epoiesen hos</em> = he did as...) mirrors OT compliance patterns (Gen 6:22; Exod 12:50 — Noah and Israel "did as God commanded") — Joseph as the obedient servant of the divine will, regardless of personal cost or public scrutiny.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>heos hou eteken huion</strong> — until she bore a son — the conjunction <em>heos hou</em> (until) establishes a temporal boundary: the statement describes what obtained during the pregnancy. Greek <em>heos hou</em> does not grammatically imply the resumption of the condition after the boundary event; the text makes no statement about the state of the marriage after the birth. Matthew\'s concern is entirely with the virgin birth and the legal naming of the child. <strong>Kai ekalesen to onoma autou Iesoun</strong> — and he called his name Jesus — Joseph\'s naming of the child is the legal act of paternity that establishes Jesus\'s Davidic lineage.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "1": '<p><strong>magoi</strong> (<em>magi</em>, plural of <em>magos</em>) — originally a priestly caste of Persian Zoroastrians skilled in astronomy and interpretation of signs; by the 1st century the term had broadened to include wise men, court astrologers, and interpreters of omens throughout the eastern Mediterranean. Matthew specifies neither their number nor royal status (both are later church traditions derived from the three gifts of v.11 and Psalm 72:10-11). <strong>apo anatolon</strong> — from the east — the same direction as the Babylonian exile; now wise men from the nations seek the Jewish King.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>ton astera autou en te anatole</strong> — his star in the rising/east — <em>anatole</em> can mean "east" (the direction) or "rising" (of a star: heliacal rising, the first appearance of a star above the eastern horizon at dawn, an astronomically significant event). The magi may have seen the star "in its rising" — at its first appearance. The definitive article (<em>ton astera autou</em> = his star) assumes prior knowledge of a messianic astral sign; Numbers 24:17 ("a star shall come out of Jacob") provides the OT background.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>etarachthe</strong> — he was troubled, disturbed — aorist passive of <em>tarasso</em> (to agitate, throw into confusion; used in 14:26 of the disciples seeing Jesus on the water and in 27:65 for the disturbed watchers at the tomb). Herod\'s disturbance is political: a rival king of the Jews threatens his Idumean dynasty. <strong>Kai pasa Ierosolyma met\' autou</strong> — and all Jerusalem with him — the city\'s collective anxiety parallels its rulers\'; whether from genuine messianic concern or fear of Herod\'s violent reaction to perceived challenges is left ambiguous by Matthew.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>archiereis kai grammateis tou laou</strong> — chief priests and scribes of the people — <em>archiereis</em> (chief priests, plural) encompasses the ruling priestly families, not merely the current high priest. <em>Grammateis</em> (Torah-scribes, learned interpreters) are distinguished from the Pharisees (not mentioned here) and function as the official biblical scholars. Their role is deeply ironic: they correctly identify Bethlehem (v.5) as the messianic birthplace from scripture but do not go to seek the child — biblical knowledge without response.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The chief priests and scribes cite Micah 5:2 without hesitation: <em>en Bethleem tes Ioudaias</em> — in Bethlehem of Judea — the specification "of Judea" distinguishes this Bethlehem from the Galilean Bethlehem (Josh 19:15). Their citation is accurate; their indifference is the irony. The learned authorities of Jerusalem know the scripture that the Magi (Gentiles from the east) had followed by astral observation. Matthew contrasts pagan seekers with Jewish experts: the Gentiles travel; the experts inform without moving.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Micah citation (5:2) is modified significantly: <em>oudamos elachiste ei en tois hegesin Iouda</em> — by no means are you least among the rulers of Judah — changes the MT\'s "too small" to a positive declaration, and adds <em>hostis poimanei ton laon mou ton Israel</em> (who will shepherd my people Israel) from 2 Sam 5:2 (David\'s commission). The composite citation (Micah + 2 Samuel) is characteristic of Matthew\'s interpretive freedom in demonstrating scriptural coherence: the Messianic ruler is both Davidic birthplace (Micah) and Davidic shepherd-king (2 Sam).</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>ton chronon tou phainomenou asteros</strong> — the time of the appearing star — <em>phainomai</em> (present participle: the appearing, manifesting star) describes the star as currently visible/manifest. Herod determines the time <strong>akribos</strong> (exactly, precisely — the same adverb repeated in v.8 for his commission to the Magi). This precise timing becomes the basis for the massacre calculation in v.16: "two years old and under, according to the time he had determined." The detail is not incidental; it sets up the subsequent atrocity.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>akribos exetasate</strong> — search carefully/precisely — the adverb <em>akribos</em> (exactly, precisely) repeats Herod\'s precision motif from v.7. The command to search carefully serves as the deceptive frame for his stated pious purpose (<em>hopOs kagO elthon proskyneso auto</em> — so that I too may come and worship him). Matthew presents the irony without editorial comment: the language of religious devotion (<em>proskyneso</em> = worship) is borrowed to cloak murder. The Magi are unwitting instruments of Herod\'s information-gathering.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>kai idou ho aster</strong> — and behold, the star — the <em>idou</em> (behold!) signals the narrative\'s highlighting of a key event: the star\'s reappearance after their Jerusalem visit. <strong>Proegen autous</strong> — it went before them — the imperfect <em>proegen</em> (was going before) indicates ongoing movement of the star ahead of the Magi. <strong>Heos elthon estathē epano hou en to paidion</strong> — until having come it stood over where the child was — the aorist passive <em>estathē</em> (was stationed, halted) suggests a definitive stopping. The star-guidance echoes the wilderness pillar (Exod 13:21) in leading God\'s people to his purposes.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>Echaresan charan megalen sphodra</strong> — they rejoiced a very great joy — the cognate construction (verb <em>chairo</em> + related noun <em>chara</em>) is a Hebraism (equivalent to the Hebrew infinitive absolute) used to intensify the expression: they rejoiced greatly. The adverb <em>sphodra</em> (very greatly, exceedingly) further intensifies. The construction appears in the LXX for superlative joy (e.g., 1 Kgs 1:40). The Magi\'s response to finding the star stationary is unbounded relief and celebration, marking the climactic resolution of their long journey.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>prosekynesan auto</strong> — they worshiped/did obeisance to him — <em>proskyneo</em> (to fall before in worship or homage) is Matthew\'s primary verb for worship of Jesus throughout the Gospel (8:2; 9:18; 14:33; 15:25; 28:9, 17) and for worship of God alone (4:10). The Magi perform before the infant what the disciples will perform before the risen Lord. <strong>Edoran auto dora</strong> — they offered him gifts — the noun <em>dora</em> (gifts, offerings) carries cultic overtones: these are tribute-offerings appropriate to a king and to worship. The three gifts (gold, frankincense, myrrh) are rich but their symbolic interpretation (royalty, priesthood, burial) is post-Matthean tradition.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>Chresmatisthentes kat\' onar</strong> — having been warned by a divine oracle in a dream — <em>chrematizo</em> in the passive (to receive a divine oracle, divine communication) is stronger than a general dream: the Magi receive a specific divine directive. The verb is used in LXX for divine responses (Jer 29:23; 37:2) and in NT for divine warnings (Heb 8:5; 11:7). <strong>Di\' alles hodou anechoresan</strong> — through another road they withdrew — <em>anachoreo</em> (to withdraw, retire: used throughout Matt 2 for strategic repositioning) describes the Magi\'s obedient departure by an alternate route, thwarting Herod\'s intelligence-gathering.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>Phyge eis Aigypton</strong> — flee into Egypt — <em>pheugo</em> (aorist imperative: flee!) conveys urgency. The command is delivered at night and obeyed at night (<em>nyktos</em>). Egypt as refuge is historically plausible (large Jewish population in Alexandria) and typologically resonant: the land of Israel\'s slavery becomes the Messiah\'s sanctuary. <strong>Heos an eipo soi</strong> — until I tell you — the conditional <em>an</em> with subjunctive (<em>eipo</em> = tell) makes the return contingent on a future divine communication, maintaining the pattern of Joseph\'s complete dependence on divine direction.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>Anastas paralaben to paidion kai ten metera autou nyktos</strong> — having risen he took the child and his mother by night — the aorist participle <em>anastas</em> (having risen, stood up) is the same root as <em>anastasis</em> (resurrection), here simply "got up from sleep." The night departure mirrors the urgency of the Exodus (Exod 12:31-42: Israel departed from Egypt at night). <strong>Anechoreosen eis Aigypton</strong> — he withdrew into Egypt — the verb <em>anachoreo</em> appears again (vv.12, 13, 14, 22) as Matthew\'s term for divinely-directed strategic movement.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>Ex Aigyptou ekalesa ton huion mou</strong> — out of Egypt I called my son — the citation of Hosea 11:1 in the MT (the LXX reads differently: <em>ta tekna autou</em> = his children). Matthew follows the MT reading, which has the singular "my son." Hosea 11:1 originally refers to Israel\'s exodus as God\'s son called out of Egypt. Matthew applies this typologically to Jesus: Israel as "son" collectively is the type; Jesus as "Son" individually is the antitype who recapitulates and surpasses Israel\'s history. The <em>hina plerothe</em> formula frames this as fulfillment of a deeper pattern, not merely verbal prediction.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>Ethumothē lian</strong> — he was furious/enraged greatly — <em>thymoo</em> (to be enraged, infuriated) is a strong word for violent anger; the adverb <em>lian</em> (greatly, exceedingly) intensifies it. <strong>Anaireo</strong> — to do away with, kill — a strong term also used for executions (Acts 2:23; 7:52 of Jesus\'s death). <strong>Apo dietons kai katateron kata ton chronon hon ekribosen para ton magon</strong> — two years old and under, according to the time he had precisely determined from the Magi — the calculation explains the two-year range: Herod builds in a margin of error from the star\'s appearance time.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>Tote eplerothe to rhēthen dia Ieremiou</strong> — then was fulfilled what was spoken through Jeremiah — note the absence of <em>hina</em> (in order that) that appears in other fulfillment formulas (1:22; 2:15, 23; 4:14). The adverb <em>tote</em> (then, at that time) replaces the purpose conjunction: Matthew does not say the massacre happened in order to fulfill, but that it was then fulfilled — a pastorally sensitive distinction that avoids making the children\'s deaths merely instrumental to prophetic fulfillment while still insisting on the scriptural correspondence.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The Jeremiah 31:15 citation: <strong>phone en Rama ekousthe, klauthmos kai odyrmos polys</strong> — a voice was heard in Ramah, weeping and great mourning — the aorist passive <em>ekousthe</em> (was heard) treats the prophetic text as a past event now seen in correspondence with a present event. Rachel weeping for her children (<em>ta tekna autes</em>) is a matriarchal mourning for descendants. The location of Ramah in Benjamin\'s territory (near Bethlehem in Judah\'s tribal area) was a deportation staging point for the Babylonian exiles (Jer 40:1). Matthew sees a structural correspondence between the Babylonian exile\'s weeping and Herod\'s massacre.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>Teleutesantos de tou Herodou</strong> — after Herod died — the genitive absolute construction (<em>teleuteo</em> = to die, reach one\'s end) marks the temporal boundary of Jesus\'s Egyptian exile. Herod the Great died in 4 BCE, confirming that the birth of Jesus occurred before 4 BCE. <strong>Idou angelos kyriou phainetai kat\' onar</strong> — behold, an angel of the Lord appears in a dream — the fourth occurrence of the divine-dream-announcement formula in Matthew 1-2 (1:20; 2:12, 13, 19), marking the sustained pattern of divine communication to Joseph throughout the infancy narrative.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>Tethnekasin gar hoi zetountes ten psychen tou paidiou</strong> — for those who were seeking the child\'s soul/life are dead — the plural <em>tethnekasin</em> (perfect: have died and remain dead) and <em>hoi zetountes</em> (those who were seeking) are a precise verbal allusion to Exod 4:19 LXX where God tells Moses "for all those who were seeking your life are dead." Matthew\'s verbal echo is exact: Jesus\'s return from Egypt recapitulates Moses\'s return to Egypt after the death of those who sought his life, positioning Jesus as the new Moses from the very beginning of his life.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>Anastas paralaben to paidion kai ten metera autou</strong> — having risen he took the child and his mother — the obedience formula repeats exactly (cf. v.14 departure formula), creating a structural parallel: departure (v.14) and return (v.21) framed by identical language. The <em>anastas</em> (having risen) + <em>paralaben</em> (took) sequence signals Joseph\'s immediate and complete compliance with the divine instruction, without deliberation or delay — the same pattern as v.24 (ch.1) where he took Mary as his wife after the angel\'s instruction.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>Archelaus basileuei tes Ioudaias anti tou patros autou Herodou</strong> — Archelaus is reigning over Judea instead of his father Herod — Herod Archelaus (ruled 4 BCE–6 CE) was notorious for cruelty; he was deposed by Rome after Jewish complaints of his harsh rule and sent into exile. <strong>Phobētheis ekei apelthein</strong> — he was afraid to go there — the aorist passive <em>phobētheis</em> (having been made afraid, terrified) is a divine or providential fear, confirmed by a dream-warning. Joseph\'s fear is both rational (Archelaus\'s reputation) and divinely validated.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>Nazōraios klethesetai</strong> — he will be called a Nazarene — the formula cites "the prophets" (plural, <em>dia ton propheton</em>) but no single OT text contains this phrase. Most likely explanations: (1) wordplay on Hebrew <em>nezer</em> (branch, shoot: Isa 11:1 — "a <em>nezer</em> from Jesse\'s roots") — the Nazarene/branch connection; (2) possible connection to <em>Nazir</em> (Nazirite, consecrated one: Num 6; Judg 13); (3) typological use of "prophets" as composite reference rather than single verbal citation. Matthew\'s formula signals prophetic fulfillment at the pattern level, not the specific-quotation level.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "1": '<p><strong>En de tais hemerais ekeinais</strong> — in those days — a temporal bridge after the summary of Jesus\'s childhood in Nazareth (2:23). The phrase is vague about the intervening period (Jesus\'s childhood and youth are unnarrated). <strong>Iōannes ho baptistēs</strong> — John the baptizer — the active participle used as a title (<em>baptistēs</em>), denoting one who regularly baptizes. <strong>Keryssōn en te eremo tes Ioudaias</strong> — proclaiming in the wilderness of Judea — <em>keryssōn</em> (herald-proclaiming, present participle) indicates ongoing public proclamation; the wilderness of Judea is the Jordan River valley, which immediately fulfills the Isaiah 40:3 oracle cited in v.3.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>Phone boontos en te eremo</strong> — a voice crying in the wilderness — the Isaiah 40:3 citation follows the LXX (which differs from the MT in punctuation: the MT places the wilderness with "prepare the way," but the LXX and Matthew place it with the crying: a voice crying in the wilderness). This punctuation locates John\'s wilderness ministry as the fulfillment-marker. <strong>Hetoimasate ten hodon kyriou</strong> — prepare the way of the Lord — <em>kyrios</em> in the LXX citation translates the Tetragrammaton (YHWH) in Isaiah; Matthew applies it to John\'s preparation for Jesus, implying Jesus is the YHWH whose way is being prepared.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>trichōmatos kamēlou</strong> — camel\'s hair — the same description as Elijah in 2 Kgs 1:8 LXX (<em>anēr dasys</em> = a hairy man, <em>zōnēn dermatinēn</em> = leather belt). Matthew\'s readers would recognize the Elijah-correspondence (confirmed in 11:14; 17:12-13). <strong>Akridas kai meli agrion</strong> — locusts and wild honey — locusts were a permitted food under Levitical law (Lev 11:22); wild honey from rock or tree was a wilderness food (Deut 32:13; 1 Sam 14:25-26). Both are subsistence foods that locate John outside civilized society as a prophetic figure living on creation\'s provision.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>Exeporeueto pros auton Ierosolyma kai pasa he Ioudaia kai pasa he perichoros tou Iordanou</strong> — Jerusalem was going out to him, and all Judea, and all the region around the Jordan — the imperfect <em>exeporeueto</em> (was going out, kept going out) indicates an ongoing, sustained movement of people over an extended period. The triple <em>pasa</em> (all) — all Jerusalem, all Judea, all the Jordan region — emphasizes the national scope and intensity of John\'s revival. The geographic compression (center of power + entire province + the border region) signals a movement of whole-population dimensions.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>Ebaptizonto en to Iordane potamo hyp\' autou</strong> — they were being baptized by him in the Jordan River — the imperfect passive <em>ebaptizonto</em> indicates ongoing, continuous action: crowds were being baptized one after another over an extended period. <strong>Exomologoumenoi tas hamartias auton</strong> — confessing their sins — the present participle <em>exomologoumenoi</em> (openly confessing, acknowledging publicly) indicates that the verbal confession accompanied the immersion, making baptism a public act of acknowledged sinfulness. <em>Exomologeo</em> in the middle voice (making a confession on behalf of oneself) carries the sense of voluntary, frank acknowledgment before God and witnesses.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>Gennēmata echidnōn</strong> — offspring of vipers — the vocative combines genealogical metaphor (<em>gennēmata</em> = offspring, products of generation) with viper-imagery. <em>Echidna</em> (viper, adder) was considered particularly dangerous; the offspring inherit the parent\'s character and venom. <strong>Tis hypedexen hymin phygein apo tēs mellousēs orgēs</strong> — who warned you to flee from the coming wrath? — the aorist <em>hypedexen</em> (showed, pointed out beforehand) implies someone tipped them off. The question is rhetorically sarcastic: the Pharisees and Sadducees have come to secure the baptismal credential without genuine repentance.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>Karpous axious tēs metanoias</strong> — fruit worthy of repentance — the plural <em>karpous</em> (fruits) suggests multiple visible evidences; a singular fruit would suggest one definitive act. <em>Axios</em> (worthy, proportional, of appropriate weight) measures the fruit against the repentance: genuine repentance produces correspondingly genuine behavioral evidence. The metaphor of fruit-bearing is used throughout Matthew for the test of authentic profession (7:16-20; 12:33; 21:43) — trees are known by their fruit, not by their claims.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>Patrikas echomen ton Abraam</strong> — we have Abraham as our father — the claim of Abrahamic descent as covenantal security was a firmly held conviction in Second Temple Judaism: descent from Abraham placed one within the covenant and its protections. <strong>Ek tōn lithōn toutōn dunatos estin ho theos egeirai tekna tō Abraam</strong> — from these stones God is able to raise up children for Abraham — the wordplay between <em>lithōn</em> (stones) and <em>tekna</em> (children) may reflect an Aramaic pun: <em>bnaya</em> (children) vs. <em>abnaya</em> (stones). <em>Egeirai</em> (to raise up) is also the resurrection verb — God who raises from the dead can raise children from stones.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>Ēdē de hē axinē pros tēn rizan tōn dendrōn keitai</strong> — already the axe is lying at the root of the trees — <em>ēdē</em> (already, now) makes this present urgency rather than future threat: the axe is not being raised; it is already positioned. The present participle <em>keitai</em> (lies, is placed) confirms its current location. <strong>Pan dendron mē poioun karpon kalon ekkoptetai</strong> — every tree not producing good fruit is cut down — the present <em>ekkoptetai</em> functions either as a gnomic present (describing the invariable rule) or as an anticipatory present of imminent action: the cutting down is as certain as if it is already happening.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>Baptizō hymas en hydati eis metanoian</strong> — I baptize you in water for/unto repentance — the preposition <em>en</em> is instrumental (by means of water); <em>eis metanoian</em> (unto repentance) indicates purpose or result: the water-baptism is oriented toward repentance. The contrast with Jesus\'s baptism <strong>en pneumati hagiō kai pyri</strong> — in/with the Holy Spirit and fire — maintains the instrumental <em>en</em>: the Spirit and fire are the media of Jesus\'s baptizing. <strong>Hou ouk eimi hikanos ta hypodēmata bastasai</strong> — whose sandals I am not worthy to carry — sandal-carrying was slave-service; the Baptist places himself below slave-status relative to the coming one.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>Ptyon en tē cheiri autou</strong> — the winnowing fork is in his hand — <em>ptyon</em> is the wooden fork used to toss threshed grain into the wind so the lighter chaff separates from the heavier wheat. The present tense (<em>estin</em> implied) makes this present reality, not future promise. <strong>Diakathariein tēn alōna autou</strong> — to thoroughly clean his threshing floor — <em>diakathariō</em> (compound verb with <em>dia</em> = through + <em>kathariō</em> = cleanse) indicates complete, thorough cleaning. <strong>Achyron katakausei pyri asbesto</strong> — the chaff he will burn with unquenchable fire — <em>asbestos</em> (inextinguishable, quenchless) appears in the LXX for inescapable divine judgment (Isa 34:10; 66:24; Jer 7:20).</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>Tote paraginetai ho Iēsous apo tēs Galilaias epi ton Iordanēn pros ton Iōannēn</strong> — then Jesus arrives from Galilee to the Jordan to John — the historical present <em>paraginetai</em> (arrives, comes alongside) brings the narrative into vivid immediacy. This is Jesus\'s first appearance in Matthew since his childhood in Nazareth (2:23); Matthew gives no account of the intervening years. The <em>tote</em> (then) connects John\'s ministry as the preparation and Jesus\'s arrival as the fulfillment of that preparation — what the Baptist announced, the one he announced now arrives.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>Diekolyen auton</strong> — he was trying to prevent/deter him — the imperfect <em>diekolyen</em> suggests persistent, repeated attempts to hinder rather than a single objection. <strong>Egō chreian echō hypo sou baptisthēnai</strong> — I have need to be baptized by you — the emphatic pronoun <em>egō</em> (I) contrasts with the implied "you"; the construction <em>hypo sou</em> (by you) identifies Jesus as the one who should be baptizing John, not the reverse. The need (<em>chreian</em>) John acknowledges is his own spiritual need for the Spirit-baptism that only Jesus can give (v.11).</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>Prepon hēmin estin plērōsai pasan dikaiosynēn</strong> — it is fitting for us to fulfill all righteousness — <em>prepon</em> (fitting, proper, becoming) is the language of theological and moral appropriateness. <strong>Pasan dikaiosynēn</strong> — all righteousness — the scope is comprehensive: this one act fulfills the entirety of what God\'s salvific plan requires. Jesus\'s baptism is not a confession of sin (he has none) but a covenant-identification with God\'s people, a commissioning act, and the inauguration of the mission. The plural <em>hēmin</em> (for us) includes both Jesus and John in the propriety of the act.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>Anebē apo tou hydatos</strong> — he came up from the water — <em>apo</em> (from away from) with the water indicates prior immersion: he came up out of it. <strong>Ēneōchthēsan autō hoi ouranoi</strong> — the heavens were opened to him — <em>anoigō</em> in the aorist passive (<em>ēneōchthēsan</em>) echoes Ezek 1:1 LXX (<em>ēnoichthēsan hoi ouranoi</em> = the heavens were opened) at the inauguration of Ezekiel\'s prophetic ministry. <strong>Peristeron</strong> — a dove — in Jewish tradition (b. Chagigah 15a) the Spirit at creation hovered like a dove over the waters (Gen 1:2); the Spirit\'s dove-form at Jesus\'s baptism signals a new-creation inauguration.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>Houtos estin ho huios mou ho agapētos</strong> — this is my beloved Son — <em>agapētos</em> (beloved, uniquely loved) in the LXX at Gen 22:2 translates Hebrew <em>yahid</em> (only, uniquely beloved son) for Isaac at the Aqedah; the term carries the resonance of the uniquely-loved son whose offering is demanded. The declaration combines Ps 2:7 (royal investiture: "You are my Son") with Isa 42:1 (Servant commissioning: "in whom I am well pleased") — king and Servant in one announcement. <strong>En hō eudokēsa</strong> — in whom I am well pleased — the aorist <em>eudokēsa</em> (I took delight, was pleased) may be a timeless aorist or refer to the delight in the obedience just completed.</p>'
  },
  "4": {
    "1": '<p><strong>Tote ho Iēsous anēchthē eis tēn erēmon hypo tou pneumatos</strong> — then Jesus was led up into the wilderness by the Spirit — the aorist passive <em>anēchthē</em> (<em>anagō</em> = to lead up) makes the Spirit the explicit agent: the Spirit leads Jesus into the wilderness for testing. This recapitulates Israel\'s Spirit/cloud-led wilderness journey (Exod 13:21-22; Num 9:15-23). <strong>Peirasthēnai hypo tou diabolou</strong> — to be tested/tempted by the devil — <em>peirazo</em> means both external testing (to prove quality) and internal temptation (to induce sin); the same word is used for Israel\'s wilderness testing (Deut 8:2: God tested Israel; here the devil tests Jesus).</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>Nēsteusas hēmeras tessarakonta kai nyktas tessarakonta</strong> — having fasted forty days and forty nights — the dual formula (days and nights) precisely parallels Moses\'s Sinai fast (Exod 34:28; Deut 9:9, 18: both forty days and forty nights) and Elijah\'s wilderness fast (1 Kgs 19:8: forty days and forty nights to Horeb). Jesus recapitulates both figures. <strong>Husteron epeinasen</strong> — afterward he was hungry — the aorist <em>epeinasen</em> (he became hungry) is the physiological trigger: genuine human hunger is the entry-point for the tempter. The forty-day fast is completed; the vulnerability is real.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>Ei huios ei tou theou</strong> — if you are the Son of God — <em>ei</em> with present indicative is a first-class condition assuming the reality: "since you are the Son of God..." The tempter does not deny the sonship but attempts to redirect it toward self-service. <strong>Eipe hina hoi lithoi houtoi artoi genōntai</strong> — tell these stones to become bread — the aorist subjunctive <em>genōntai</em> (become) requests a creative word, a use of divine-son power for immediate physical self-provision. The temptation is to deploy the power of sonship for private benefit rather than for the mission to which the Father has called.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>Gegraptai</strong> — it is written, it stands written — the perfect passive of <em>graphō</em> (to write): the scripture has been written and its authority remains in effect. Jesus\'s triple use of <em>gegraptai</em> (vv.4, 7, 10) positions his responses as authoritative appeals to standing divine word, not ad hoc arguments. The Deuteronomy 8:3 citation: <strong>ouk ep\' artō monō zēsetai ho anthrōpos</strong> — man shall not live by bread alone — directly addresses Israel\'s wilderness murmuring for food; Jesus, unlike Israel, trusts the Father\'s provision and does not demand bread from stone.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>Tēn hagian polin</strong> — the holy city — Matthew\'s distinctive designation for Jerusalem (also 27:53), reflecting the city\'s sanctified cultic status. <strong>Pterygion tou hierou</strong> — the pinnacle/parapet of the temple — <em>pterygion</em> (diminutive of <em>pteryx</em>, wing) = wing, parapet, or projecting edge; used for the highest point of the temple complex. According to Josephus (Antiquities 15.11.5), the southeast corner of the temple platform overlooks a sheer drop of several hundred feet into the Kidron Valley — a height sufficient to make the test of angelic protection dramatically visible.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The devil cites Psalm 91:11-12 (LXX 90): <strong>tois angelois autou enteleitai peri sou</strong> — he will command his angels concerning you — but omits the clause "to guard you in all your ways" that follows in the Psalm. The omission strips the promise from its covenantal context (the path of covenant obedience) to make it a basis for presumption (demanding miraculous rescue to prove God\'s care). Jesus\'s counter (Deut 6:16) identifies this as "putting the Lord to the test" — exactly the misuse of divine promise that the Psalm\'s context guards against.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>Gegraptai palin</strong> — it is written again — Jesus meets the devil\'s scripture-citation with another scripture-citation, demonstrating that the devil\'s use of Ps 91 requires correction by Deut 6:16, not by denying the Psalm. <strong>Ouk ekpeiraseis kyrion ton theon sou</strong> — you shall not put the Lord your God to the test — Deuteronomy 6:16 explicitly cites the Massah incident (Exod 17:1-7) where Israel demanded water as a test of God\'s presence. The verb <em>ekpeiraseis</em> (future indicative, from <em>ekpeirazō</em>) means to put to an extreme test, to demand proof by creating a crisis. Jesus refuses to engineer a rescue to prove the Father\'s faithfulness.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>Oros hypsēlon lian</strong> — a very high mountain — <em>lian</em> (very, exceedingly) intensifies the height beyond any natural geography. The mountain may be visionary or apocalyptic rather than a specific physical peak — Matthew does not identify it. <strong>Pasas tas basileias tou kosmou kai tēn doxan autōn</strong> — all the kingdoms of the world and their glory — <em>pasas</em> (all, every) and <em>doxan</em> (glory, splendor, magnificence) make the offer genuinely comprehensive. Whether the vision was literal or representative, Matthew presents Jesus\'s response as treating the offer as real — which gives his refusal its full moral weight.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>Tauta soi panta dōsō ean pesōn proskunēsēs moi</strong> — all these I will give to you if having fallen you worship me — the conditional <em>ean</em> with aorist subjunctive presents a single, decisive act: one moment of submission. <strong>Pesōn</strong> (having fallen) describes the prostration of worship; combined with <em>proskunēsēs</em> (do obeisance, worship) the action is unmistakable. The verb <em>proskyneō</em> is used throughout Matthew for worship of Jesus (2:11; 8:2; 14:33; 28:9, 17) and for the proper worship of God alone (4:10) — the devil demands the specific act reserved for God.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>Hypage, Satana</strong> — go away, Satan — the imperative <em>hypage</em> (depart, go away) is authoritative dismissal; the naming <em>Satana</em> (transliteration of Hebrew <em>Satan</em>, the Adversary) identifies the tempter definitively for the first time in the exchange. The name will recur at Peter\'s rebuke (16:23: "<em>Hypage opiso mou, Satana</em>" — the verbatim repetition there is deliberate). The Deuteronomy 6:13 citation: <strong>Kyrion ton theon sou proskunēseis kai autō monō latreueis</strong> — you shall worship the Lord your God and him alone you shall serve — the emphatic <em>monō</em> (alone, only) is not in the MT but appears in Matthew\'s text.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>Kai idou angeloi prosēlthon kai diēkonoun autō</strong> — and behold, angels came to him and were serving/ministering to him — <em>idou</em> (behold!) signals a significant moment. <em>Prosēlthon</em> (aorist: came to, approached) is followed by the imperfect <em>diēkonoun</em> (were serving, ministering — continuous action): the angels provide sustained care, not a single act. <em>Diakonein</em> (to serve, minister) is the same word for table-service (Matt 8:15; 25:44; 27:55) — the angels provide physical care (food and rest?) after the extended fast. The episode recalls Elijah\'s angelic refreshment after his own wilderness fast (1 Kgs 19:5-8).</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>Akousas de hoti Iōannēs paredothē</strong> — but having heard that John was handed over — <em>paradidōmi</em> (to hand over, deliver up) is Matthew\'s term for betrayal and arrest (17:22; 20:18; 26:2, 15, 21, 23, 24, 25, 45, 46, 48); its use for John\'s arrest prefigures the same fate for Jesus. <strong>Anechōrēsen eis tēn Galilaian</strong> — he withdrew into Galilee — <em>anachoreo</em> (to withdraw, retire strategically) is used throughout Matthew 2 for divinely-guided repositioning; its reappearance here frames Jesus\'s Galilean move as theologically intentional rather than a retreat from danger.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>Katōkēsen eis Kapharnaoum tēn paraliian</strong> — he took up residence in Capernaum by the sea — <em>katōkēsen</em> (aorist of <em>katoikeo</em>, to settle, take up permanent residence — stronger than temporary lodging) indicates Capernaum became Jesus\'s home base for the Galilean ministry. The descriptor <em>paraliia</em> (coastal, by the sea) locates Capernaum on the shore of the Sea of Galilee, important for the following Isaianic citation\'s mention of "the Way of the Sea." <strong>En horiois Zaboulōn kai Nephaleim</strong> — in the regions of Zebulun and Naphtali — the tribal territories frame the prophetic fulfillment.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>Hina plērōthē to rhēthen dia Ēsaiou tou prophētou</strong> — so that what was spoken through Isaiah the prophet might be fulfilled — the fifth <em>hina plērōthē</em> fulfillment formula in Matthew 1-4 (1:22; 2:15, 23; 4:14), each marking a new stage in the Christological fulfillment sequence. <em>Legontos</em> (present participle = who says) treats Isaiah\'s oracle as a living word still speaking — the prophet\'s voice is not past tense but present, awaiting its moment of actualization. The formula signals to Matthew\'s readers that this geographic relocation is not accidental but prophetically determined.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The Isaiah 9:1 citation: <strong>Gē Zaboulōn kai gē Nephaleim</strong> — land of Zebulun and land of Naphtali — the territories of the northern tribes, first to fall to Assyria in 732 BCE (2 Kgs 15:29). <strong>Hodos thalassēs, peran tou Iordanou</strong> — the Way of the Sea, beyond the Jordan — <em>hodos thalassēs</em> is the ancient trade and military road running along the Mediterranean coast and through the Jordan valley (the Via Maris of Latin tradition). <strong>Galilaia tōn ethnōn</strong> — Galilee of the Gentiles — the mixed-population region where Gentiles lived alongside Jews, appropriate for a ministry that will eventually extend to all nations (28:19).</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>Ho laos ho kathēmenos en skotia phōs eiden mega</strong> — the people sitting in darkness saw a great light — the present participle <em>kathēmenos</em> (sitting, dwelling) describes a state of settled habitation in darkness, not merely passing through it. <strong>Phōs eiden mega</strong> — they saw a great light — the aorist <em>eiden</em> is punctiliar: a decisive, singular moment of seeing. <strong>Tois en chōra kai skia thanatou</strong> — to those in the region and shadow of death — <em>skia thanatou</em> (shadow of death) is a compound expression found in Ps 22:4; 23:4 (LXX); Job 3:5 for the deepest darkness. Isaiah\'s oracle of reversal — darkness to light — is fulfilled in Jesus\'s Galilean ministry.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>Apo tote erxato ho Iēsous kēryssein</strong> — from that time Jesus began to proclaim — <em>apo tote</em> (from that time) is a Matthean structural marker used at key narrative transitions (also 16:21 for the beginning of passion-announcements; 26:16). <strong>Kēryssō</strong> (to herald, proclaim) is the verb of public announcement by a royal herald — Jesus speaks as one with authority to make public declarations about the kingdom. The message is identical to John\'s (3:2): <strong>metanoeite, ēngiken gar hē basileia tōn ouranōn</strong> — but Jesus proclaims it as the one in whom the kingdom is present, not merely approaching.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>Amfiblēstron</strong> — a casting net — the specific net-type (<em>amphiblestron</em>, a net thrown so it spreads in a circle and closes like a bag around the fish) distinguishes from the dragnet (<em>sagēnē</em>, 13:47) used from a boat. The present participle <em>ballontas</em> (throwing, casting) indicates the brothers were actively at work fishing when Jesus encountered them — their occupation was fully engaged, making the call\'s interruption and their response more striking. <strong>Hēsan gar halieis</strong> — for they were fishermen — the explanatory imperfect identifies their occupation and qualifications for the metaphor Jesus will use.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>Deute opisō mou</strong> — come after me — the imperative <em>deute</em> (come!, plural) combined with <em>opisō mou</em> (behind me, after me) is the standard teacher-disciple relationship formula: to come after a rabbi was to follow in his path, learn his way, and eventually replicate his teaching. <strong>Poiēsō hymas halieis anthrōpōn</strong> — I will make you fishers of people — the word-play on their occupation: the same <em>halieuo</em> (to fish) now describes their mission. The metaphor is active: fishing requires skill, effort, and going to where the fish are.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>Hoi de eutheos aphentes ta diktya ēkolouthēsan autō</strong> — they immediately left the nets and followed him — <em>eutheos</em> (immediately, at once) is a Matthean marker of decisive, unhesitating response. <strong>Aphentes</strong> (having left/abandoned) carries the weight of real cost: the nets (their livelihood and family business equipment) are left behind. <strong>Ēkolouthēsan autō</strong> — they followed him — the aorist of <em>akoloutheo</em> (to follow, accompany in discipleship) is used throughout Matthew for committed following (8:22-23; 9:9; 10:38; 16:24; 19:21, 27, 28).</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>Katartizontas ta diktya auton</strong> — mending/repairing their nets — the present participle <em>katartizontas</em> (from <em>katartizō</em>, to restore, mend, put in order) indicates the ongoing work of net repair between fishing expeditions — a normal part of the fisher\'s routine. The verb also means "to equip" or "make complete" (used in Eph 4:12 for equipping the saints; 1 Cor 1:10 for being united in the same mind). James and John are at work in the boat with their father Zebedee (<em>meta Zebedaiou tou patros auton</em>) — the family business context frames the cost of the call.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>Aphentes to ploion kai ton patera auton</strong> — leaving the boat and their father — the objects left by James and John include both property (the boat, the family business) and family relationships (their father). Matthew\'s parallel structure (Peter and Andrew / James and John) is deliberate: the two pairs are called in identical circumstances and respond identically (<em>eutheos</em>/<em>aphentes</em>/<em>ēkolouthēsan</em> = immediately/having left/followed). The escalating cost (nets → nets + boat + father) is highlighted by the parallel construction.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>Periēgen en holē tē Galilaia</strong> — he was going about in all of Galilee — the imperfect <em>periēgen</em> (was going about, was traveling through) indicates an extended, ongoing campaign throughout the region. Three simultaneous activities described by present participles: <strong>didaskon</strong> (teaching, in the synagogues), <strong>kēryssōn</strong> (proclaiming the gospel of the kingdom), and <strong>therapeuōn</strong> (healing every disease and every infirmity). <strong>Pasan noson kai pasan malakian</strong> — every disease and every weakness/infirmity — the double <em>pasan</em> (every) emphasizes comprehensive scope; <em>malakia</em> (weakness, infirmity) covers conditions that are not strictly diseases.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>Apēlthen hē akoē autou eis holēn tēn Syrian</strong> — the report/news of him went out into all of Syria — <em>akoē</em> (report, news, hearing) is the word for what is heard about someone; the phrase marks the first explicit geographic extension of Jesus\'s fame beyond Jewish territory to the Roman province of Syria (north and east of Galilee). <strong>Daimonizoumenous kai selēniazomenous kai paralytikous</strong> — those possessed by demons and those who were moonstruck (epileptics?) and those who were paralyzed — the three categories cover demonic affliction, neurological/psychiatric conditions, and physical paralysis.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>Ēkolouthēsan autō ochloi polloi</strong> — great crowds followed him — the verb <em>akoloutheo</em> (to follow) appears again, now applied to crowds rather than disciples; in Matthew the word carries both levels of meaning (physical accompanying and committed discipleship). The five geographic sources — <em>apo tēs Galilaias kai Dekapoleōs kai Ierosolymōn kai Ioudaias kai peran tou Iordanou</em> — cover virtually all the Jewish population regions: the Galilean heartland, the Gentile Decapolis, the capital and its province, and Transjordan (Perea). The gathering from all directions sets the stage for the Sermon on the Mount (5:1-2).</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-original', 'matthew')
    merge_comm(existing, MATTHEW)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'matthew', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Matthew mkt-original: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
